observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management observe the following courses of actions:
The Inventory Committee perform complete inventory-taking and ensure that all accountable persons present the items under their custody and put/ update the property tags at the same time;
The Inventory Committee submit a revised RPCPPE based on the actual physical count all PPE items of the Municipality and reconcile with the records of the Municipal Accountant;
Management consider complying with the One-Time Cleansing of PPE account balances prescribed under COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020; and
Municipal Accountant reclassify the semi-expendable items and the related Accumulated Depreciation to the appropriate accounts and thereafter, observe the ₱15,000.00 capitalization threshold when classifying/ recording a tangible item as PPE.

Management: 
submit immediately the lacking documents and liquidation reports from the barangays;

instruct the Accountant to make the necessary adjustments to correct the balances of the relevant accounts;

henceforth, ensure that financial assistance to barangays is supported with the necessary documents to ensure the diligent and judicious utilization of public funds.

We reiterated our  prior years’ audit recommendations which should be implemented within the year so as not to have them reiterated almost every year:

The Municipal Mayor should create a new Inventory Committee whose members can devote more time in conducting the mandated periodic physical count of all Property, Plant & Equipment (PPE);

The Municipal Treasurer to properly classify/identify the PPEs by maintaining property cards to ascertain its existence, valuation and accuracy;

Reconciliation for any difference between the result of the physical count and accounting records is made to ensure the accuracy and reliability of the PPE account balance as presented in the financial statements at year-end.

